theories, inequality, and the Russian invasion of Ukraine. He argues that effective responses to these problems require understanding how information is generated and spread. Bringing together empirical findings about the psychological and social mechanisms that drive cognitive errors with philosophical accounts of critical thinking, Thagard develops an innovative theory of how we gain information. Grasping how the generation and transmission of knowledge can fail helps us find ways to repair it and provides tools for converting misinformation into facts. Offering a deep and rich account of the nature and workings of information, Falsehoods Fly provides practical, concrete strategies to stop the creation and spread of misinformation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aDisinformationxSocial aspects. 0aInformation integrityxSocial aspects. 0aInformation sciencexSociological aspects. 0aMisinformationxSocial aspects. 0aTruthfulness and falsehoodxSocial aspects. 7aSCIENCE / Cognitive Science.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/thag2139440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231560115423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231560115/original  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles